s-later-studios-disrupted-themselves-to-invent-broadcast-tv ) we discussed =
China=E2=80=99s recent economic turmoil and Bing vs. Google six months afte=
r Sydney.

On to the Update:

Arm=E2=80=99s F-1
---------

From CNBC ( https://www.cnbc.com/2023/08/21/arm-files-for-nasdaq-listing-as=
-softbank-sells-shares-in-chipmaker.html ) :

Arm Ltd., the British company whose circuit designs lie inside billions of =
electronic devices, said profit fell by more than 50% in the most recent qu=
arter in filings that kicked off what is expected to be the biggest initial=
 public offering of the year. Arm raised lofty expectations for its busines=
s overall but faces near-term market challenges. Sales of smartphones =E2=
=80=94 a core market for Arm=E2=80=99s circuit designs =E2=80=94 have slowe=
d in recent quarters, including a 7.8% decline in the second quarter, accor=
ding to International Data Corporation. The company reported $675 million o=
f revenue in its latest quarter, ended in June, down from $692 million the =
year prior. It reported that net income more than halved to $105 million in=
 the quarter.

Arm is one of the world=E2=80=99s most important semiconductor businesses, =
serving companies such as Apple, Qualcomm and Advanced Micro Devices, which=
 rely on it for some of their chips. Arm has served as a neutral party to t=
he chip industry=E2=80=94offering its designs to everyone without favoring =
any one company. The market Arm is targeting =E2=80=94 chips that contain p=
rocessors and go into smartphones, personal computers, televisions, servers=
, cars and networking equipment =E2=80=94 should grow by nearly 7% a year t=
o reach around $247 billion by the end of 2025, the company said in a filin=
g with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Arm=E2=80=99s revenue repres=
ents a small sliver of that total today, but the company said it expected t=
he cost and complexity of chip design would increase, =E2=80=9Cresulting in=
 our royalties comprising a greater proportion of each chip=E2=80=99s total=
 value.=E2=80=9D

Arm=E2=80=99s F-1 ( https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1973239/0001193=
12523216983/d393891df1.htm ) is interesting reading, albeit not always for =
the reasons that Softbank might wish. Start with the good news: I think the=
 prospectus lays out a sensible opportunity for Arm going forward.

First, there are the growth opportunities in the industries Arm serves. Thi=
s includes secular opportunities in smart devices and autos, and the opport=
unity to take share in PCs and servers. However, this is countered by the f=
act that Arm=E2=80=99s most important market, smartphones, is fully saturat=
ed at this point.

Second, Arm argues that chip design is becoming more complex:

The resources required to develop leading-edge products are significant and=
 continue to increase exponentially as manufacturing process nodes shrink. =
According to IBS, IC design costs were approximately $249 million for a 7nm=
 chip and approximately $725 million for a 2nm chip, representing approxima=
tely a three-times increase in design cost as compared to a 7nm chip. Desig=
n partners play an increasingly valuable role in the chip design process by=
 providing specialized capabilities and expertise that enable semiconductor=
 suppliers to focus on their core product differentiation, while keeping pa=
ce with market innovation. Design partners facilitate innovation and enhanc=
e customers=E2=80=99 competitive positioning by reducing the complexity, ri=
sk, and cost of a significant part of the development cycle. For example, t=
o design a 2nm chip, IBS estimates that the software development, verificat=
ion, and IP qualification is 71% of the overall cost. In addition, design p=
artners, like Arm, that can demonstrate a deep understanding of their custo=
mers=E2=80=99 workloads are better positioned to integrate themselves into =
their customers=E2=80=99 workflows, further expanding their value propositi=
on over time.

At the same time, Arm says that OEMs are looking for their own customized c=
hips:

Many OEMs today utilize =E2=80=9Coff-the-shelf,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cmercha=
nt,=E2=80=9D semiconductors when building their product offerings. However,=
 this approach can introduce compromises. For example, an OEM may use a chi=
p that includes features that are irrelevant for its use case, at the expen=
se of performance and cost efficiency. Similarly, an OEM may need a chip th=
at incorporates features not otherwise available from a merchant supplier. =
As a result, leading OEMs are increasingly looking to build custom chips in=
-house that deliver greater performance and greater efficiency at an equal =
or better price for a particular use case.

These two points are obviously in conflict, but Arm says it is uniquely pla=
ced to resolve said conflict.

We provide the most pervasive CPU architecture in the world. The key elemen=
ts of our solution include:

* *Arm CPUs.* The foundation of our product offerings is our market-leading=
 CPU products. Our CPU products leverage our common scalable ISA and addres=
s the widest range of performance, power, and cost requirements.
* *Other Design Offerings.* We have a portfolio of products that are deploy=
ed alongside our CPUs, including:

* *Graphics Processing Units.* We offer a family of GPU products providing =
an optimal visual experience across a wide range of devices.
* *System IP.* Complementary design components that enable designers to cre=
ate high-performance, power-efficient, reliable, and secure chips.
* *Compute Platform Products.* Arm=E2=80=99s CPU, GPU, and System IP produc=
ts integrate into a foundational compute platform optimized for a specific =
end market.

* *Development Tools and Software.* Our tools and software support the deve=
lopment and deployment of our offerings.

We continue to expand the scope of our product offerings, investing in more=
 holistic, end-market optimized designs, expanding beyond individual design=
 IP to providing subsystem designs. Given the complexities of developing ch=
ips using the most advanced manufacturing processes, we are making signific=
ant investments to better support the increasing number of OEMs looking to =
develop their own customized chips=E2=80=A6

Our solution allows customers to build optimized chips, while reducing thei=
r design execution risk and their internal development costs. We generally =
expect to license our products to multiple customers, enabling us to comple=
tely cover the cost of developing new Arm products by charging each license=
e only a portion of the total development costs. We invest significant time=
, resources and effort in the design and verification of each processor and=
 work closely with our partners to ensure a standard of excellence in the p=
rocessor products we deliver to our customers.

Arm trumpets other growth opportunities as well, including new licensing of=
ferings that makes Arm designs more accessible for startups, which has long=
 been a pain point with Arm=E2=80=99s traditional licenses, but this bit ab=
ove is the core of the growth proposition: Arm as system designer for the e=
ntire industry =E2=80=94 i.e. more than just CPUs =E2=80=94 at a time when =
custom chips are both more desirable and more expensive.

Arm=E2=80=99s Risks
-----------

The most obvious risk is that this plan may not come to fruition, particula=
rly given the fact that there is tangible evidence of the industry going th=
e other way, and not just Apple. Qualcomm in particular is back in the chip=
-design business; CEO Cristiano Amon told me in a Stratechery interview ( h=
ttps://stratechery.com/2023/an-interview-with-qualcomm-ceo-cristiano-amon/?=
access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9u=
bGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLC=
JhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0c=
mF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIzL2FuLWludGVydmlldy13aXRoLXF1YWxjb21tLWNlby1jcmlzdGlh=
bm8tYW1vbi8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTY5NTM4OTAzMywiaWF0IjoxNjkyNzk3MDMzLCJpc3MiOiJodHR=
wczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2=
xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZ=
XVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.c807mjNFlcQpfHqHc2opDRP5x=
Wiouev2cYFv2iYybnCAmfUpDeFpdhg2OTBpJcED6JUHz81Q0Q6JQeuvvYVgBlsA7BNm9U26Pny7=
rXvkxpupIXdpShlt_PdBchHvIAR3TqThTp93r0b44m4QFZ-nP-Z69oMqNBUkmOzFVC5wvvd9s2s=
hL-5H6FxAcPjkmvziFPoBDaAaHU7ZS8hSYlTkhqfzDfW1KO2wwMB0dfbqszP_IZVemqcYy1okgh=
aHO3ffcj1dAfoUrkYrpdxVTn5MqmQ77lycWMVMogfn2xaMyDD27HKICRLhCc4LbNRh9lRYJHXz8=
jL00921iTzuiWyoDg ) :

We invested in other areas, started licensing CPUs from Arm, but then we ha=
d exactly the same situation happening again. We started on this journey wi=
th Microsoft, to build the next generation PC, we are the Arm ISA partner o=
f Microsoft, we=E2=80=99re using the Windows on Snapdragon, and we realized=
 that we needed a CPU that wasn=E2=80=99t available in the ecosystem, that =
could be the leader in performance in the segment. That=E2=80=99s when we a=
cquired Nuvia, and I think that Nuvia has been integrated into Qualcomm and=
 we have been developing our own custom CPU called Oryon, and it=E2=80=99s =
going to be applied across our entire portfolio of products. The first inst=
ance is on PCs and it=E2=80=99s history repeating itself. We needed to go d=
evelop something because we believe the level of performance is going to be=
 required for leadership is not available in the ecosystem, and we=E2=80=99=
re very bullish about what we can do with our new SOC, including our Oryon =
CPU.

This gives extra weight to Arm=E2=80=99s ongoing legal war with Qualcomm ab=
out whether or not Nuvia=E2=80=99s architectual license is still valid; it=
=E2=80=99s not just a question of Arm enforcing its rights (to be determine=
d by a court), but also about protecting its entire growth thesis, particul=
arly given that Qualcomm is one of Arm=E2=80=99s biggest customers.

Arm=E2=80=99s largest customer, though, is Arm China, and the risks here ar=
e pretty wild:

* First, all revenue from Chinese OEM=E2=80=99s flows through Arm China; th=
at was 24% of revenue last year.
* Second, Arm has no control over Arm China; a Softbank-owned subsidiary do=
es have a 48% equity interest in Arm China, but control rests in Chinese en=
tity hands.
* Third, Arm China=E2=80=99s payments to Arm are based on data provided by =
Arm China, and Arm admits that =E2=80=9CIn the past, we have had issues obt=
aining timely and accurate information from Arm China.=E2=80=9D
* Fourth, Arm China regularly makes late payments =E2=80=94=C2=A0its behind=
 as of this filing =E2=80=94 and Arm has little recourse other than cajolin=
g to get its money on time.
* Fifth, while Arm China is contractually prohibited from developing its ow=
n IP (it can develop derivative products from Arm=E2=80=99s IP), Arm has no=
 way to monitor this.

Note that all of these issues are independent from the bizarre episode wher=
e the former head of Arm China attempted to hijack the subsidiary completel=
y; that was resolved (pending lawsuits), but its hard to feel good as an in=
vestor about the complete lack of control over the biggest part of Arm=E2=
=80=99s business. Oh, and for what its worth, Arm is still liable from an I=
P perspective for all of the products Arm China sells!

That=E2=80=99s not the end of it, though: obviously Arm is subject to the B=
iden export controls, and it is also dependent on TSMC for most of its chip=
s, which has its own risk factors. There is also RISC-V, the open-source IS=
A that is big in China in particular. These three are more =E2=80=9Cnormal=
=E2=80=9D risk factors, to be sure, but they are notable in that they accen=
tuate the risk from Arm China being a potentially rogue actor; taken as a w=
hole they point to a scenario where Arm=E2=80=99s best-case scenario in Chi=
na =E2=80=94 which again, is collectively its biggest customer =E2=80=94 is=
 a controlled decline.

Arm=E2=80=99s Price
-----------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/business/deals/softbank-=
buys-vision-funds-stake-in-arm-at-64-billion-valuation-52a8b41 ) last week:

SoftBank Group recently bought a 25% stake in Arm Ltd. that was held by the=
 Japanese technology investor=E2=80=99s Vision Fund unit, in a deal that va=
lues the chip designer at slightly more than $64 billion, according to peop=
le familiar with the matter. The deal signals the valuation SoftBank could =
aim to achieve from Arm=E2=80=99s much anticipated initial public offering =
in New York next month. The offering is expected to be the largest IPO this=
 year.

Arm does say in its filing that =E2=80=9CThe purchase price paid by SoftBan=
k Group to acquire shares in Arm Limited from SoftBank Vision Fund may not =
be, and should not be treated as, indicative of the trading price of our AD=
Ss following the completion of this offering.=E2=80=9D That certainly feels=
 like something that was included at a lawyer=E2=80=99s insistence, because=
 it seems pretty obvious that a $64 billion valuation is exactly what Masay=
oshi Son is shooting for. At the same time, that lawyer should get a raise,=
 because that valuation is nuts.

Just to put that number in context, Nvidia, which reports earnings this aft=
ernoon, is valued at $1.13 trillion; that is off of a revenue base of $26.9=
7 billion last fiscal year, with net income of $4.37 billion. That was, I s=
hould note, half of the profit of fiscal year 2022, thanks to substantial i=
nventory write-offs; the net result is that Nvidia is valued at 41x revenue=
, and 259x profit (again, that profit was artificially depressed). Arm, mea=
nwhile, had $2.68 billion in revenue in FY2023, and $524 million in FY2023;=
 a $64 billion valuation would be 24x revenue and 122x profit. Reasonable, =
right?

Of course not: I kind of cheated in the last paragraph, by giving you Nvidi=
a=E2=80=99s valuation right now, but revenue and profit numbers that were r=
eported on February 22. Back then Nvidia=E2=80=99s valuation was 45% of wha=
t it is now, which was about 19x revenue and 116x profit (and again, that p=
rofit was half of what it would normally be). What changed is that last qua=
rter Nvidia blew away expectations ( https://stratechery.com/2023/nvidia-ea=
rnings-jenson-huangs-defense-training-versus-inference/?access_token=3DeyJh=
bGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6Ikp=
XVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd=
1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8y=
MDIzL252aWRpYS1lYXJuaW5ncy1qZW5zb24taHVhbmdzLWRlZmVuc2UtdHJhaW5pbmctdmVyc3V=
zLWluZmVyZW5jZS8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTY5NTM4OTAzMywiaWF0IjoxNjkyNzk3MDMzLCJpc3MiOi=
JodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhc=
nRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI6=
IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.uDlmrqPXzxUpVHs294Sk=
aII0eWHLQQETiXjU2CO7NMpeaHiVn10v9mRjmwgzB2kHmWZi9DhgyZJmHUUrDgyVp6eiaNlI5p2=
zRm9WjpB5D51PPmug26FImARcfD2y3dMjvPflXc-dcx1A1KB7AS69bPIBJd6vNRL8BhwQQ82MWO=
fVcdusSABp4SHDEBtV1ll3WD_1zZQFCTp-CkQdXXtB_tLBfl9zD-99nDSpfoT5IxHZOAXF8XQmb=
X0X0SIJGjyRRv8iSw3uDZzi4jYrq8qHDGnMdKloGAf0GhvhltSwl6G9QeOirCne_YvLBHuWJcMX=
pwdVmU49uZrPEW3GQzmOQw ) , beating revenue expectations by 50% and projecti=
ng revenue growth this past quarter of 64%. That growth is what investors a=
re paying for, and it=E2=80=99s growth that Arm just hasn=E2=80=99t have; i=
n fact, revenue shrunk last year.

The big difference between Nvidia and Arm, and the reason they should be va=
lued differently, is that Nvidia sells the best chips for the current AI bo=
om with the best ecosystem. Arm, for all of its importance, doesn=E2=80=99t=
 have the best chips (Apple does), has a severely diluted ecosystem based m=
ostly on open-source software, and makes most of its money from a product (=
smartphones) that is no longer growing. This is not to take away from Arm a=
nd its contributions to the industry or even its growth plan, which as I no=
ted above is cogent enough; it=E2=80=99s just hard to see it being worth wh=
at Softbank is valuing it at.

There is, I should note, one possible reason to expect the price to be a bi=
t higher than you might expect: Nikkei reported earlier this month ( https:=
//asia.nikkei.com/Business/Tech/Semiconductors/Apple-Samsung-to-invest-in-A=
rm-as-it-eyes-September-IPO ) that Apple, Samsung, Nvidia, and Intel will a=
ll invest in Arm:

The Vision Fund will sell 10% to 15% of its Arm shares on the open market. =
Arm plans to welcome the big chipmakers as medium- to long-term shareholder=
s, selling them stakes of a few percent each. This is meant to stabilize th=
e stock price at the time of the listing.

We=E2=80=99ll see how well that works, or at what price these companies buy=
 in, but for what it=E2=80=99s worth, this is a good move for all of them: =
Arm really is an important piece of the ecosystem, and a lot of these compa=
nies were very eager to keep it out of the hands of Nvidia; lending some su=
pport to the company isn=E2=80=99t charity, but rather a recognition that e=
veryone benefits if Arm can make a go of it on its own.

